    <node id="claim:0001">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">NICE API stores all historical guideline versions queryable by year and ID</data>
      <data key="d2">0.75</data>
      <data key="d22">True</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:03", "chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d24">person:steve-ashford</data>
      <data key="d25">Steve Ashford challenged this, noting that two years ago NICE said old versions were only available via the National Archive. Joao maintained the documentation supports it for at least back to 2015.</data>
      <data key="d26">The NICE API has all the historical guidelines already saved and structured. You just need to pass the right parameters (year, ID) to retrieve old versions. No need to maintain history on Kumulus's side. Earliest confirmed queryable year: 2015.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "this NIS API has all the historical guidelines already saved and you know, structured and the answer is Yes... You just need to pass the right parameters to get that.", "ts": 257, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "about two years ago I asked them whether we could get old versions of guidelines and they said the only way to get them was to go to the National Archive.", "ts": 277, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0002">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Medbrief already has compliance certifications required to obtain the NICE API key</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:03", "chapter:04"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">Medbrief already has the compliance certifications that NICE requires to grant API key access, which means Medbrief may be able to obtain the key faster than a typical applicant.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "you guys already have the compliance certifications that they ask for to get the API key, so you might get it faster.", "ts": 237, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0003">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Every medical-legal case will contain handwritten notes in some form</data>
      <data key="d2">0.95</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:03", "chapter:04"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:steve-ashford</data>
      <data key="d26">Every case, without exception, will have handwritten notes of some kind — Lloyd George envelopes, nursing notes, or handwritten observation charts. Even trusts now using digital systems still have older handwritten records.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "Every case, every case will have handwritten notes of some way, shape or form, every single one.", "ts": 188, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0004">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">A typical case references one but sometimes two or three NICE guidelines</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:03", "chapter:04"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:steve-ashford</data>
      <data key="d26">Normally a case references one guideline, but it can quite often be two or three, particularly where the patient has multiple conditions (e.g. obstetrics plus diabetes). Simpler cases such as a fall in hospital would reference one guideline.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "I probably say, normally, no, no. It's one, but you can quite often be two or three... It depends on the case.", "ts": 125, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0005">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">NICE previously directed users to National Archive for old guideline versions</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:steve-ashford</data>
      <data key="d26">Approximately two years before this meeting, NICE told Steve Ashford that the only way to retrieve old guideline versions was through the National Archive. NICE said they were looking into making their own archive accessible but had not confirmed it at that time.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "about two years ago I asked them whether we could get old versions of guidelines and they said the only way to get them was to go to the National Archive, you see. So, but they did say they were going to look into whether they could make their archive available.", "ts": 960, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0006">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Medbrief's existing Document Intelligence OCR output can be reused by Kumulus</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:04"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">Medbrief already runs OCR on handwritten notes using Document Intelligence. Kumulus can reuse this OCR output rather than performing OCR from scratch, which remains out of scope.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "are you guys already doing OCR on the hand reading? If so, can we use this OCR on our project? Yes. Okay, okay, that helps a lot.", "ts": 742, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0007">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Cases must be compared against the NICE guideline version current at the time of the clinical event</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:04", "chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:steve-ashford</data>
      <data key="d26">If a case dates from four years ago, the comparison must use the NICE guideline version that was in force at that time — not the current version. The NICE website only shows the latest version; older versions must be retrieved separately.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "if somebody had a case that dated back four years ago, when it happened, you would need to look at the guidelines associated with that condition at that time. Now, if the guidelines have been updated, the NICE website will only show you the latest version of the guidelines.", "ts": 555, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0008">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Sending PII to LLMs is too risky even within Azure AI Foundry</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:06"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">Even when using Azure AI Foundry/Azure OpenAI models within the Azure boundary, sending patient PII to LLMs is considered a compliance breach and too risky; all PII must be pseudonymised before LLM calls.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "Even when using Azure Foundry models, it's too risky. We don't want to share PII information that's a breach of compliance.", "ts": 1330, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0009">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Databricks with Spark is best-in-class for parallel processing of unstructured medical-legal data</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:07"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">For workloads with large volumes of unstructured data requiring parallel processing, Databricks with Apache Spark is the best-in-class choice; Microsoft Fabric would be slower and less suitable.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "Databricks is the best to win the market for doing parallel processing using Spark, so if you want a solution that's fast and reliable. That's Databricks.", "ts": 1992, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0010">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Medbrief already has clinician-reviewed ground truth for sample cases</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:08"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:laura-gongas</data>
      <data key="d26">For the sample cases to be used in the PoV, a clinician has already reviewed them and the breach determinations are known, providing ready-made ground truth for evaluation of the comparison layer.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "the cases that we are going to send over to you, a clinician has already gone through them. So we already know which reaches were there. So that's a way that we could use, like as a ground truth", "ts": 2200, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0011">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Entity dimensions must be scoped per-case to prevent cross-case identity confusion</data>
      <data key="d2">0.75</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:06"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">The lookup table dimensions (patient, doctor, etc.) must be separated per case to prevent accidentally linking an entity from one case to a different case.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "we are tying up per case. So in this way we don't get lost or the challenge is to not create confusion.", "ts": 1360, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0012">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Engagement estimated at 10-12 weeks</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:10"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">10 weeks for delivery activities plus 2 weeks for testing and validation, totalling approximately 12 weeks. This is larger than the standard 6-8 week POV.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "We are estimating 10 weeks. attribute everything and two weeks for testing and validation and final tweaks. So that's a three months project we are looking here.", "ts": 2731, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0013">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Microsoft funding deadline is 12 weeks from project start</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:10"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">Microsoft requires the POV solution to be delivered within 12 weeks of start. Exceeding this deadline risks losing the Microsoft incentive funding entirely.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "Microsoft funding is related to timing of completion of the project. So if we block on some milestone or we delay a lot the project, we are at a high risk of losing the Microsoft incentives.", "ts": 2739, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0014">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Azure cost estimate capped at approximately $700/month including 30% buffer</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">Kumulus's Azure cost calculator shows an estimated maximum of approximately $700 per month for the MVP, inclusive of a 30% contingency buffer. John expects actual spend to be lower. Databricks is the dominant cost component.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "that's a 30% buffer here, okay, that I always put. I don't think we are going to leverage $700 a month for this MVP.", "ts": 3154, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0015">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Full service cost is approximately £35,000 before Microsoft incentives</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:12"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">The total undiscounted price for Kumulus's proposed engagement is approximately £35,000.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "the total price of service cost is thirty-five.", "ts": 3479, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0016">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Microsoft funding reduces cost by approximately £22,000</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:12"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">Kumulus is applying two Microsoft incentive funding streams (Data POV and AI POV) which together reduce the engagement cost by approximately £22,000.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "We were able to reduce that for almost 22, 000 pounds using Microsoft funding.", "ts": 3481, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0017">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Net cost to Medbrief after Microsoft incentives is £13,000</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d22">False</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:12"]</data>
      <data key="d23">person:joao-margura</data>
      <data key="d26">After applying both the Data POV and AI POV Microsoft incentive streams, the net cost to Medbrief for the full in-scope engagement is £13,000.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "with that discount, the end price is 13,000 pounds, with everything is in scope.", "ts": 3487, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
