    <node id="visual:case-guideline-logic-ch08">
      <data key="d0">VisualContext</data>
      <data key="d1">Case vs NICE Guideline Logic: 5-Step Process Flow</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:08"]</data>
      <data key="d27">chapframe-08.png</data>
      <data key="d28">2293.0</data>
      <data key="d29">Five-step process flow: (1) Identify Context, (2) Select Version, (3) Extract Facts, (4) Compare, (5) Output.</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "CASE VS NICE GUIDELINE LOGIC\n1. IDENTIFY CONTEXT 2. SELECT VERSION 3. EXTRACT FACTS 4. COMPARE 5. OUTPUT", "ts": 2293, "source": "frames.json", "frame": "chapframe-08.png"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="topic:gf0002">
      <data key="d0">Topic</data>
      <data key="d1">Five Formal Project Objectives (verbatim)</data>
      <data key="d30">João stated five named project objectives: (1) validate the NICE integration with the API; (2) improve the case data processing and extraction; (3) resolve entities; (4) prove secure AI usage; (5) demonstrate case versus guideline comparison.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "So these are the five main objectives. Validate the needs integration with the API, improve the case data processing, extraction, resolve entities, prove secure AI usage, demonstrate cases versus guideline comparison.", "ts": 243, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0003">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">System will not provide clinical or legal conclusions — only guideline alignment or deviation</data>
      <data key="d26">The system's output is limited to stating whether a procedure followed or deviated from the guideline and why. No clinical or legal verdict will be provided. Kumulus explicitly stated they are not doctors or judges; the tool provides evidence for human decision-makers, not the decision itself.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.95</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "No clinical or legal conclusions will be provided. We are going to say if the case we're following, the guideline or not... it's not our work to say we are not, we are not doctors or, you know, judge. So we are going to provide all the tools and necessary information to take a decision and understand what happened, but it's not in our scope to say if it is, you know, right or no.", "ts": 846, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0004">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Model fine-tuning is explicitly out of scope; pre-trained Foundry/Azure OpenAI models will be used as-is</data>
      <data key="d26">LLM fine-tuning is out of scope for the MVP. Kumulus will use Azure AI Foundry or Azure OpenAI APIs with prompt engineering only. Fine-tuning could be explored in a future phase if results are insufficient.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "AI and reasoning scope, so model fine tuning. The model fine tuning is out of scope as we are going to use Azure AI Foundry APIs or Azure Open AI APIs. We are not fine tuning the model right now. This could be explored in the future if needed.", "ts": 839, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="topic:gf0005">
      <data key="d0">Topic</data>
      <data key="d1">Entity dimension schema: five named types — patient, doctor, hospital, case, document</data>
      <data key="d30">João specified the initial entity dimension schema by name: patient, doctor, hospital, case, and document. These five are the baseline types for the PoV; additional types can be added in future phases.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:06"]</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "We are going to create the dimensions that I told you last time, so patient, doctor, hospital, case, and document for now. In the future, we can expand", "ts": 315, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0007">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Anonymisation compliance certification is out of scope for the PoV</data>
      <data key="d26">Obtaining formal compliance certification for the anonymisation component is explicitly out of scope. The engagement builds an MVP implementation of pseudonymisation, not a production-certified solution.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.9</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "NCN anonymization, compliance certification is out of scope. Of course, we're just doing an MVP. We're not creating a solution to get a certification. That's very important.", "ts": 836, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0008">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">PoV NICE API integration enables future full-catalog ingestion with no new integration work</data>
      <data key="d26">Although only the guidelines relevant to the selected cases will be ingested during the PoV, the same API integration can be used to ingest the full NICE catalog in the future without any new integration development.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "the full catalog ingestion is not in scope for this first phase, but you are going to be able to ingest all the needs catalog if you want with the API integration we are going to connect. We are just bringing what's necessary for the use case, but it's the same API.", "ts": 813, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:gf0011">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Fabric is an acceptable choice only if slow batch processing is tolerable; Databricks is required for responsive parallel workloads</data>
      <data key="d26">João drew an explicit performance trade-off: if Medbrief is willing to run the pipeline and wait an hour for results, an alternative tool to Databricks could be considered. For a solution that needs to be fast and reliable under production load, Databricks is the only recommendation.</data>
      <data key="d2">0.85</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d9">[{"quote": "If you want a solution that you can run the process and wait for one hour and get done, maybe we can take a look in other tools. But for me, that's the best in class for your use case in your scenario.", "ts": 771, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:01">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Introductions and Screen Share</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:01"]</data>
      <data key="d31">1</data>
      <data key="d32">SPEAKER_02 (Medbrief) opens the meeting, introduces John from Kumulus, and invites him to present. John shares his screen after a brief technical fumble.</data>
      <data key="d33">5.451</data>
      <data key="d34">59.011</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:02">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Proposal Overview and Context Recap</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:02"]</data>
      <data key="d31">2</data>
      <data key="d32">John recaps the proposal scope: gathering NICE guideline data, comparing it with medical-legal case documents, data anonymisation, and data tokenisation. He outlines what the presentation will cover.</data>
      <data key="d33">59.011</data>
      <data key="d34">229.0</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:03">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">In-Scope and Out-of-Scope Definition</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:03"]</data>
      <data key="d31">3</data>
      <data key="d32">John walks through the fixed-fee scope boundaries: one medical domain, one or two real cases, entity extraction, anonymisation, and an initial case-vs-guideline comparison. Out-of-scope items include handwritten note OCR from scratch, full historical NICE processing, and production application development.</data>
      <data key="d33">229.0</data>
      <data key="d34">357.571</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:04">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Q&amp;A: Guidelines, Handwritten Notes, and NICE API Access</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:04"]</data>
      <data key="d31">4</data>
      <data key="d32">Laura (Medbrief) asks about multiple NICE guideline references per case; Steve clarifies that cases typically reference one to three guidelines, rarely more. The group also discusses handwritten notes (present in every case) and confirms Medbrief's existing OCR can be reused. Laura asks about deterministic pseudonymisation and NICE API key access.</data>
      <data key="d33">357.571</data>
      <data key="d34">908.611</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:05">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">NICE API Historical Guidelines and Step 1: Data Ingestion</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:05"]</data>
      <data key="d31">5</data>
      <data key="d32">John explains that the NICE API stores historical guideline versions queryable by year and ID, reducing the need for Kumulus to maintain its own archive. Steve flags a two-year-old concern about archive availability that may now be resolved. John describes Step 1 (NICE API) and Step 2 (case PDF ingestion), including chunking and metadata strategy.</data>
      <data key="d33">908.611</data>
      <data key="d34">1141.249</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:06">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Entity Extraction, Identity Resolution, and Pseudonymisation</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:06"]</data>
      <data key="d31">6</data>
      <data key="d32">John covers Steps 3 and 4: detecting and classifying entities (patient, doctor, hospital) across documents using similarity matching, and replacing PII with deterministic tokens before sending data to LLMs. Brandon raises the need to agree an entity classification schema with Medbrief's data science team before coding begins.</data>
      <data key="d33">1141.249</data>
      <data key="d34">1979.0</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:07">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Full Architecture Walkthrough: Data Factory, Databricks, and AI Layer</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:07"]</data>
      <data key="d31">7</data>
      <data key="d32">John presents the end-to-end Azure architecture: BLOB storage, Data Factory for orchestration, Databricks for raw/silver/gold layer processing, Azure AI Foundry for LLM inference, and Azure Monitor for observability. He explains why Databricks is preferred over Microsoft Fabric for this unstructured, parallel-processing workload.</data>
      <data key="d33">1979.0</data>
      <data key="d34">2090.0</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:08">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Case-vs-Guideline Comparison Logic and Evaluation Strategy</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:08"]</data>
      <data key="d31">8</data>
      <data key="d32">John walks through the deviation-check logic: selecting a case, retrieving the matching NICE guideline version, cross-referencing clinical events, and producing an evidence pack with page-level traceability. Laura notes that clinician-reviewed ground truth already exists for the sample cases; Momoko (Medbrief) raises the challenge of evaluating pseudonymisation on handwritten content that OCR may have missed.</data>
      <data key="d33">2090.0</data>
      <data key="d34">2496.0</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:09">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Project Activities, Success Criteria, and Delivery Approach</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:09"]</data>
      <data key="d31">9</data>
      <data key="d32">John summarises the six delivery steps (scope alignment, kickoff, data processing, entity extraction, comparison, handover), outlines the WBS and Gantt approach, and reviews success criteria covering NICE API access, entity extraction, anonymisation, comparison quality, and explainability. Laura requests quantitative evaluation metrics rather than manual review.</data>
      <data key="d33">2496.0</data>
      <data key="d34">2691.0</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:10">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Microsoft Funding, Timeline, and Milestone Structure</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:10"]</data>
      <data key="d31">10</data>
      <data key="d32">John presents the 10-to-12-week timeline (two weeks for testing), framing the engagement as an MVP rather than a standard POV. He stresses the 12-week Microsoft funding deadline and confirms that Medbrief can take full ownership of deliverables at the end of milestone one without committing to a phase two.</data>
      <data key="d33">2691.0</data>
      <data key="d34">3068.0</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:11">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Azure Cost Estimates and Assumptions/Limits</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:11"]</data>
      <data key="d31">11</data>
      <data key="d32">John walks through the Azure cost calculator (capped estimate ~$700/month with 30% buffer, Databricks as the dominant cost) and reads through assumptions and fixed-fee limits: one medical domain, up to two cases, no model fine-tuning, no compliance certification, no production app integration. Laura confirms their MLOps engineer will review the infrastructure choices.</data>
      <data key="d33">3068.0</data>
      <data key="d34">3422.0</data>
      <data key="d35">[]</data>
      <data key="d36">[]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="chapter:12">
      <data key="d0">Chapter</data>
      <data key="d1">Pricing Discussion, Scope Revision, and Close</data>
      <data key="d2">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">["chapter:12"]</data>
      <data key="d31">12</data>
      <data key="d32">John reveals the full service cost of ~35,000 pounds reduced to 13,000 pounds net after Microsoft incentives across two funding streams (Data POV and AI POV). Brandon indicates Medbrief had expected full sponsorship and may prefer to resource internally; John offers to produce a revised zero-cost-to-client proposal by removing the comparison layer and leaning on Medbrief's team. The meeting closes with thanks and a five-business-day timeline for the revised proposal.</data>
      <data key="d33">3422.0</data>
      <data key="d34">3716.211</data>
